	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Soldering Iron, no more than 15 watts. Wire gauge should probably be 22 or less as in thicker. Multi-meters are handy but not required. The EPROM programmer you linked looks as though it supports the common 8bit eproms for use in NES reproductions. No you don't need anything else. All you are doing is replacing the memory, a MASKROM, with another memory, an EPROM, to change the game in the cartridge. It's very simple. The only time it's more complicated is in a few special cases where major changes are made to the board for some reason, such as Final Fantasy III (Famicom) could require modifications since there is no exact donor.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


